on and subtraction). This gives the transform many applications in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" title=3D"Science">science</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineerin=
g">engineering</a>, mostly as a tool for solving linear <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equation" title=3D"Differential equation=
">differential equations</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lynn_1986_pp._225=E2=80=932=
72_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplac=
e_transform#cite_note-Lynn_1986_pp._225%E2%80%93272-1"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_system" title=3D"Dynamical sy=
stem">dynamical systems</a> by simplifying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Ordinary_differential_equation" title=3D"Ordinary differential equ=
ation">ordinary differential equations</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Integral_equation" title=3D"Integral equation">integral equati=
ons</a> into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_equation" t=
itle=3D"Algebraic equation">algebraic polynomial equations</a>, and by simp=
lifying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution" title=3D"Conv=
olution">convolution</a> into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mult=
iplication" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_tr=
ansform#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_3-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-:1=
-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
