</p><p>The Laplace transform is related to many other transforms. It is ess=
entially the same as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mellin_tr=
ansform" title=3D"Mellin transform">Mellin transform</a> and is closely rel=
ated to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_transform" tit=
le=3D"Fourier transform">Fourier transform</a>. Unlike the Fourier transfor=
m, the Laplace transform is often an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Analytic_function" title=3D"Analytic function">analytic function</a>, me=
aning that it has a convergent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pow=
er_series" title=3D"Power series">power series</a>, the coefficients of whi=
ch represent the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_(mathemati=
cs)" title=3D"Moment (mathematics)">moments</a> of the original function. M=
oreover, the techniques of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex=
_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a>, especially <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contour_integral" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Contour integral">contour integrals</a>, can be used for simplif=
ying calculations.
</p>
