l-align: -2.338ex; width:13.152ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
int x^{s}\varphi (x)\,dx,}"></span>
akin to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mellin_transform" title=
=3D"Mellin transform">Mellin transform</a>, to transform the whole of a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Difference_equation" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Difference equation">difference equation</a>, in order to lo=
ok for solutions of the transformed equation. He then went on to apply the =
Laplace transform in the same way and started to derive some of its propert=
ies, beginning to appreciate its potential power.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transfor=
m#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Laplace also recognised that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Joseph_Fourier" title=3D"Joseph Fourier">Joseph Fourier</a>'s method of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_series" title=3D"Fourier se=
ries">Fourier series</a> for solving the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Diffusion_equation" title=3D"Diffusion equation">diffusion equation<=
/a> could only apply to a limited region of space, because those solutions =
were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_function" title=3D"P=
eriodic function">periodic</a>. In 1809, Laplace applied his transform to f=
ind solutions that diffused indefinitely in space.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transfo=
rm#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  In 1821, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Cauchy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cauchy">Cauchy</a> developed an=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operational_calculus" title=3D"Op=
erational calculus">operational calculus</a> for the Laplace transform that=
 could be used to study linear differential equations in much the same way =
the transform is now used in basic engineering.  This method was popularize=
d, and perhaps rediscovered, by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ol=
iver_Heaviside" title=3D"Oliver Heaviside">Oliver Heaviside</a> around the =
turn of the century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-13"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" title=3D"=
Bernhard Riemann">Bernhard Riemann</a> used the Laplace transform in his 18=
59 paper <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_the_number_of_prime=
s_less_than_a_given_magnitude" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"On the number=
 of primes less than a given magnitude">On the number of primes less than a=
 given magnitude</a></i>, in which he also developed the inversion theorem.=
  Riemann used the Laplace transform to develop the functional equation of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_zeta_function" title=
=3D"Riemann zeta function">Riemann zeta function</a>, and his method is sti=
ll used to relate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_form=
" title=3D"Modular form">modular transformation law</a> of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobi_theta_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Jacobi theta function">Jacobi theta function</a>, which is simple t=
o prove via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_summation" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Poisson summation">Poisson summation</a>, to th=
e functional equation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-14"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hjalmar_Mellin" title=3D"Hj=
almar Mellin">Hjalmar Mellin</a> was among the first to study the Laplace t=
ransform, rigorously in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_W=
eierstrass" title=3D"Karl Weierstrass">Karl Weierstrass</a> school of analy=
sis, and apply it to the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Differential_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Differential equatio=
ns">differential equations</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Special_functions" title=3D"Special functions">special functions</a>, at t=
he turn of the 20th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-15"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>  At around the same time, Heaviside was busy with his operational ca=
lculus.  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Joannes_Stieltjes"=
 title=3D"Thomas Joannes Stieltjes">Thomas Joannes Stieltjes</a> considered=
 a generalization of the Laplace transform connected to his <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stieltjes_moment_problem" title=3D"Stieltjes mome=
nt problem">work on moments</a>.  Other contributors in this time period in=
cluded <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathias_Lerch" title=3D"Mat=
hias Lerch">Mathias Lerch</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-16"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Heaviside" title=
=3D"Oliver Heaviside">Oliver Heaviside</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Thomas_John_I%27Anson_Bromwich" title=3D"Thomas John I'Anson =
Bromwich">Thomas Bromwich</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-17"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>In 1929, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vannevar_Bush" tit=
le=3D"Vannevar Bush">Vannevar Bush</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Norbert_Wiener" title=3D"Norbert Wiener">Norbert Wiener</a> publis=
hed <i>Operational Circuit Analysis</i> as a text for engineering analysis =
of electrical circuits, applying both Fourier transforms and operational ca=
lculus, and in which they included one of the first predecessors of the mod=
ern table of Laplace transforms.
In 1934, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raymond_Paley" title=3D"R=
aymond Paley">Raymond Paley</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Norbert_Wiener" title=3D"Norbert Wiener">Norbert Wiener</a> published the=
 important work <i>Fourier transforms in the complex domain</i>, about what=
 is now called the Laplace transform (see below).   Also during the 30s, th=
e Laplace transform was instrumental in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/G_H_Hardy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"G H Hardy">G H Hardy</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Edensor_Littlewood" title=
=3D"John Edensor Littlewood">John Edensor Littlewood</a>'s study of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tauberian_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Tauberian theorem">tauberian theorems</a>, and this application wa=
s later expounded on by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_tr=
ansform#CITEREFWidder1941">Widder (1941)</a>, who developed other aspects o=
f the theory such as a new method for inversion.  <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Charles_Titchmarsh" title=3D"Edward Charles Titchmar=
sh">Edward Charles Titchmarsh</a> wrote the influential <i>Introduction to =
the theory of the Fourier integral</i> (1937).
</p><p>The current widespread use of the transform (mainly in engineering) =
came about during and soon after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
orld_War_II" title=3D"World War II">World War II</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_tran=
sform#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> replacing the earlier Heaviside <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operational_calculus" title=3D"Operational ca=
lculus">operational calculus</a>. The advantages of the Laplace transform h=
ad been emphasized by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gustav_Doets=
ch" title=3D"Gustav Doetsch">Gustav Doetsch</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform=
#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> to whom the name Laplace transform is apparently=
 due.
</p>
