<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bilateral_Laplace_transform=
">Bilateral Laplace transform</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DLaplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Bilateral Laplace transform"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-sided_Laplace_transform" tit=
le=3D"Two-sided Laplace transform">Two-sided Laplace transform</a></div>
<p>When one says "the Laplace transform" without qualification, the unilate=
ral or one-sided transform is usually intended. The Laplace transform can b=
e alternatively defined as the <i>bilateral Laplace transform</i>, or <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-sided_Laplace_transform" title=3D"T=
wo-sided Laplace transform">two-sided Laplace transform</a>, by extending t=
he limits of integration to be the entire real axis. If that is done, the c=
ommon unilateral transform simply becomes a special case of the bilateral t=
ransform, where the definition of the function being transformed is multipl=
ied by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heaviside_step_function=
" title=3D"Heaviside step function">Heaviside step function</a>.
</p><p>The bilateral Laplace transform <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>(<i>=
s</i>)</span> is defined as follows:
</p>
<div class=3D"equation-box" style=3D"margin: 0 0 0 1.6em;padding: 5px; bord=
er-width:2px; border-style: solid; border-color: #0073CF; color: inherit;te=
xt-align: center; display: table">
<p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"=
mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math=
 xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle F(s=
)=3D\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }e^{-st}f(t)\,dt.}">
