a -iT}^{\gamma +iT}e^{st}F(s)\,ds,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5efafcd962aa264ad91c3e5dc7b73c07970776a5" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.671ex; width:47.767ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle f(=
t)=3D{\mathcal {L}}^{-1}\{F\}(t)=3D{\frac {1}{2\pi i}}\lim _{T\to \infty }\=
int _{\gamma -iT}^{\gamma +iT}e^{st}F(s)\,ds,}"></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(<=
span id=3D"math_Eq._3" class=3D"reference nourlexpansion" style=3D"font-wei=
ght:bold;">Eq. 3</span>)
</p>
</div>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B3</=
span> is a real number so that the contour path of integration is in the re=
gion of convergence of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>(<i>s</i>)</span>. I=
n most applications, the contour can be closed, allowing the use of the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residue_theorem" title=3D"Residue the=
orem">residue theorem</a>. An alternative formula for the inverse Laplace t=
ransform is given by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post%27s_inve=
rsion_formula" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Post's inversion formula">Pos=
t's inversion formula</a>. The limit here is interpreted in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weak_topology#Weak-*_topology" title=3D"Weak =
topology">weak-* topology</a>.
</p><p>In practice, it is typically more convenient to decompose a Laplace =
transform into known transforms of functions obtained from a table and cons=
truct the inverse by inspection.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Probability_theory">Probabi=
lity theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Laplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Probability theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D=
"Probability theory">pure</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Applied_probability" title=3D"Applied probability">applied probability</a>,=
 the Laplace transform is defined as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected value">expected value</a>. If <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable=
">random variable</a> with probability density function <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span>, then the Laplace transform=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> is g=
iven by the expectation
