    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle F(s)=3D(s-s_{=
0})\int _{0}^{\infty }e^{-(s-s_{0})t}\beta (t)\,dt,\quad \beta (u)=3D\int _=
{0}^{u}e^{-s_{0}t}f(t)\,dt.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/99e8feba04b19cd2c61d80c1ed00bed66332bc6e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.338ex; width:62.038ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle F=
(s)=3D(s-s_{0})\int _{0}^{\infty }e^{-(s-s_{0})t}\beta (t)\,dt,\quad \beta =
(u)=3D\int _{0}^{u}e^{-s_{0}t}f(t)\,dt.}"></span>
</p><p>That is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>(<i>s</i>)</span> can effec=
tively be expressed, in the region of convergence, as the absolutely conver=
gent Laplace transform of some other function.  In particular, it is analyt=
ic.
</p><p>There are several <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paley%E2%=
80%93Wiener_theorem" title=3D"Paley=E2=80=93Wiener theorem">Paley=E2=80=93W=
iener theorems</a> concerning the relationship between the decay properties=
 of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i></span>, and the properties of the Lapl=
ace transform within the region of convergence.
</p><p>In engineering applications, a function corresponding to a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_time-invariant_system" title=3D"Li=
near time-invariant system">linear time-invariant (LTI) system</a> is <i>st=
able</i> if every bounded input produces a bounded output. This is equivale=
nt to the absolute convergence of the Laplace transform of the impulse resp=
onse function in the region <span class=3D"texhtml">Re(<i>s</i>) =E2=89=A5 =
0</span>. As a result, LTI systems are stable, provided that the poles of t=
he Laplace transform of the impulse response function have negative real pa=
rt.
</p><p>This ROC is used in knowing about the causality and stability of a s=
ystem.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Properties_and_theorems">Pr=
operties and theorems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DLaplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Properties and theorems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Laplace transform's key property is that it converts <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" title=3D"Derivative">differentiation<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral" title=3D"Integra=
l">integration</a> in the time domain into multiplication and division by <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> in the Laplace domain. Thus, the Lap=
lace variable <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> is also known as an <=
i>operator variable</i> in the Laplace domain: either the <i>derivative ope=
rator</i> or (for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup>)</s=
pan> the <i>integration operator</i>.
</p><p>Given the functions <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>(<i>t</i>)</span=
