 =3D cos(<i>=CF=89</i><sub>0</sub><i>t</i>)</span> has a Laplace transform =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>(<i>s</i>) =3D  <i>s</i>/(<i>s</i><sup>2</s=
up> + <i>=CF=89</i><sub>0</sub><sup>2</sup>)</span> whose ROC is <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">Re(<i>s</i>) &gt; 0</span>. As <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</=
i> =3D <i>i=CF=89</i><sub>0</sub></span> is a pole of  <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>F</i>(<i>s</i>)</span>, substituting <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i=
> =3D <i>i=CF=89</i></span> in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i>(<i>s</i>)</=
span> does not yield the Fourier transform of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f<=
/i>(<i>t</i>)<i>u</i>(<i>t</i>)</span>, which contains terms proportional t=
o the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirac_delta_functions" class=
