for some constants <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i></span>.  The generalized Borel transform allows a dif=
ferent weighting function to be used, rather than the exponential function,=
 to transform functions not of exponential type. <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Nachbin%27s_theorem" title=3D"Nachbin's theorem">Nachbin's t=
heorem</a> gives necessary and sufficient conditions for the Borel transfor=
m to be well defined.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fundamental_relationships">=
Fundamental relationships</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DLaplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Edit section: Fundamental relationships"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Since an ordinary Laplace transform can be written as a special case of =
a two-sided transform, and since the two-sided transform can be written as =
the sum of two one-sided transforms, the theory of the Laplace-, Fourier-, =
Mellin-, and Z-transforms are at bottom the same subject. However, a differ=
ent point of view and different characteristic problems are associated with=
 each of these four major integral transforms.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Table_of_selected_Laplace_t=
ransforms">Table of selected Laplace transforms</h2><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLaplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Table of selected Laplace transforms"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Laplace_tran=
sforms" title=3D"List of Laplace transforms">List of Laplace transforms</a>=
</div>
<p>The following table provides Laplace transforms for many common function=
s of a single variable.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-33"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For definitions and=
 explanations, see the <i>Explanatory Notes</i> at the end of the table.
</p><p>Because the Laplace transform is a linear operator,
</p>
