<p>Using this linearity, and various <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/List_of_trigonometric_identities" title=3D"List of trigonometric identit=
ies">trigonometric</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic=
_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hyperbolic function">hyperbolic</=
a>, and complex number (etc.) properties and/or identities, some Laplace tr=
ansforms can be obtained from others more quickly than by using the definit=
ion directly.
</p><p>The unilateral Laplace transform takes as input a function whose tim=
e domain is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-negative" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-negative">non-negative</a> reals, which is w=
hy all of the time domain functions in the table below are multiples of the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heaviside_step_function" title=3D=
"Heaviside step function">Heaviside step function</a>, <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>u</i>(<i>t</i>)</span>.
</p><p>The entries of the table that involve a time delay <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>=CF=84</i></span> are required to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Causal_system" title=3D"Causal system">causal</a> (meaning tha=
t <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=84</i> &gt; 0</span>).  A causal system is=
 a system where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impulse_respon=
se" title=3D"Impulse response">impulse response</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>h</i>(<i>t</i>)</span> is zero for all time <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">t</span> prior to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>t</i> =3D 0</span>. In general, the region of convergence for causal syste=
ms is not the same as that of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti=
causal_system" title=3D"Anticausal system">anticausal systems</a>.
</p>
