<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"s-domain_equivalent_circuit=
s_and_impedances"><i>s</i>-domain equivalent circuits and impedances</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLaplace_transform&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: s-domain equival=
ent circuits and impedances"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Laplace transform is often used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Network_analysis_(electrical_circuits)" title=3D"Network analysis (=
electrical circuits)">circuit analysis</a>, and simple conversions to the <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span>-domain of circuit elements can be ma=
de. Circuit elements can be transformed into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Electrical_impedance" title=3D"Electrical impedance">impedances<=
/a>, very similar to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phasor_(sine_=
waves)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Phasor (sine waves)">phasor</a> impe=
dances.
</p><p>Here is a summary of equivalents:
</p>
<dl><dd><figure class=3D"mw-halign-center skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:F=
ile/Frameless"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:S-Domain_circu=
it_equivalents.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description" title=3D"s-domain equival=
ent circuits"><img alt=3D"s-domain equivalent circuits" src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/S-Domain_circuit_equivalents.=
svg/500px-S-Domain_circuit_equivalents.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"400" height=3D"274" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"615" data=
-file-height=3D"422"></a><figcaption><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span=
>-domain equivalent circuits</figcaption></figure></dd></dl>
<p>Note that the resistor is exactly the same in the time domain and the <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span>-domain. The sources are put in if the=
re are initial conditions on the circuit elements. For example, if a capaci=
tor has an initial voltage across it, or if the inductor has an initial cur=
rent through it, the sources inserted in the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</=
i></span>-domain account for that.
</p><p>The equivalents for current and voltage sources are simply derived f=
rom the transformations in the table above.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Examples_and_applications">=
Examples and applications</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DLaplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=
=3D"Edit section: Examples and applications"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Laplace transform is used frequently in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engineering</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>; t=
he output of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_time-invaria=
nt_system" title=3D"Linear time-invariant system">linear time-invariant sys=
tem</a> can be calculated by convolving its unit impulse response with the =
input signal. Performing this calculation in Laplace space turns the convol=
ution into a multiplication; the latter being easier to solve because of it=
s algebraic form. For more information, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Control_theory" title=3D"Control theory">control theory</a>. The =
Laplace transform is invertible on a large class of functions.  Given a sim=
ple mathematical or functional description of an input or output to a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System" title=3D"System">system</a>, th=
e Laplace transform provides an alternative functional description that oft=
en simplifies the process of analyzing the behavior of the system, or in sy=
nthesizing a new system based on a set of specifications.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_=
transform#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Laplace transform can also be used to solve differential equatio=
ns and is used extensively in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mech=
anical_engineering" title=3D"Mechanical engineering">mechanical engineering=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_engineering" t=
itle=3D"Electrical engineering">electrical engineering</a>.  The Laplace tr=
ansform reduces a linear differential equation to an algebraic equation, wh=
ich can then be solved by the formal rules of algebra.  The original differ=
ential equation can then be solved by applying the inverse Laplace transfor=
m. English electrical engineer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oli=
ver_Heaviside" title=3D"Oliver Heaviside">Oliver Heaviside</a> first propos=
ed a similar scheme, although without using the Laplace transform; and the =
resulting operational calculus is credited as the Heaviside calculus.
</p>
