<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Spatial_(not_time)_structur=
e_from_astronomical_spectrum"><span id=3D"Spatial_.28not_time.29_structure_=
from_astronomical_spectrum"></span>Spatial (not time) structure from astron=
omical spectrum</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DLaplace_transform&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Spatial (not time) structure from astronomical spectrum"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The wide and general applicability of the Laplace transform and its inve=
rse is illustrated by an application in astronomy which provides some infor=
mation on the <i>spatial distribution</i> of matter of an <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomical</a> sou=
rce of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiofrequency" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Radiofrequency">radiofrequency</a> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_radiation" title=3D"Thermal radiation">thermal=
 radiation</a> too distant to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angu=
lar_resolution" title=3D"Angular resolution">resolve</a> as more than a poi=
nt, given its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_density" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Flux density">flux density</a> <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrum" title=3D"Spectrum">spectrum</a>, rather th=
an relating the <i>time</i> domain with the spectrum (frequency domain).
</p><p>Assuming certain properties of the object, e.g. spherical shape and =
constant temperature, calculations based on carrying out an inverse Laplace=
 transformation on the spectrum of the object can produce the only possible=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_model" title=3D"Math=
ematical model">model</a> of the distribution of matter in it (density as a=
 function of distance from the center) consistent with the spectrum.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Laplace_transform#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When independent information=
 on the structure of an object is available, the inverse Laplace transform =
method has been found to be in good agreement.
</p>
