o \infty }"></span>.  They are thus of importance in asymptotic formulae of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Probability=
">probability</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" =
title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, where often the spectral side has asym=
ptotics that are simpler to infer.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Feller_43-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform#cite=
_note-Feller-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Two Tauberian theorems of note are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Hardy%E2%80%93Littlewood_Tauberian_theorem" title=3D"Hardy=E2=
=80=93Littlewood Tauberian theorem">Hardy=E2=80=93Littlewood Tauberian theo=
rem</a> and  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiener%27s_Tauberian_=
theorem" title=3D"Wiener's Tauberian theorem">Wiener's Tauberian theorem</a=
>.  The Wiener theorem generalizes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Ikehara_Tauberian_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ikehara Taub=
erian theorem">Ikehara Tauberian theorem</a>, which is the following statem=
ent:
</p><p>Let <i>A</i>(<i>x</i>) be a non-negative, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function" title=3D"Monotonic function">monotonic</=
a> nondecreasing function of <i>x</i>, defined for 0&nbsp;=E2=89=A4&nbsp;<i=
>x</i>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;=E2=88=9E. Suppose that
